subject: Make req spec and RT aware of volume-backed instances
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2015-07-12 09:05:29.000000000', 'files': [], 'web_link': 'https://opendev.org/openstack/nova/commit/ef187bc759ced06a7796c915ecb270f11942742c', 'message': "Fix evaluation of host disk usage by volume-backed instances

Currently thoughout Nova instance's root_gb is used as a size of host
disk space used by the instance root volume. This leads to errors
because root_gb is assined to instance's flavor root_gb which almost
always is not 0, but the root volume of the volume-backed instance
doesn't consume space of host disk. I.e. the real value is 0, but the
used value is not 0.

Affected modules are hosts and simple_tenant_usage REST APIs, CLI manage
tool, resource_tracker, claims, notifications, host_manager.

This patch sets instance.root_gb = 0 for volume-backed instances and
keep it during instance life cycle. This gives a chance to modules above
to do work with volume-backed instances properly without modification.

Closes-Bug: #1469179
Related-Bug: #1334974
Change-Id: I0a673afafd39eca7b0d540a0efd316249c35bb58

commit_message:
Make req spec and RT aware of volume-backed instances

Currently, the flavor disk size is used for scheduling and resource
reporting of instances regardless of whether an instance has been
booted from volume. This causes problems like instances filling up
a compute host's 'local_gb' and 'local_gb_used' when in reality,
they aren't using any local disk space if they are boot from volume.
This causes a scenario where the cluster has capacity but requests
fail to schedule because hosts are reporting disk used that isn't
actually used.

This makes the request spec request 0 disk if the instance is
booted from volume and makes the resource tracker report 0 disk if
the instance is booted from volume. Added new method which will
return the image_ref of given instance. If image_ref is None then
instance is volume backed and if image_ref is not None then instance
is spawned using image.

NOTE:
Made changes in boot api to set image_ref to None if both image and
volume is provided. Similarly set image_ref to None while rebuild if
instance is boot from volume.

Closes-Bug: #1469179

Co-Authored-By: Abhishek Kekane <abhishek.kekane@nttdata.com>

Change-Id: I0a673afafd39eca7b0d540a0efd316249c35bb58

added_lines: def _volume_snapshot_check(self, gcow=None, get_guest=None, notfound=None): if gcow is not None: if gcow != 'qcow2': msg = _('Unknown delete_info type %s') % gcow raise exception.NovaException(msg) elif get_guest is not None: instance = get_guest try: guest = self._host.get_guest(instance) except exception.InstanceNotFound: raise exception.InstanceNotRunning(instance_id=instance.uuid) return guest elif notfound is not None: msg = _('Disk with id: %s ' 'not found attached to instance.') % notfound['volume_id'] LOG.debug('Domain XML: %s', notfound['xml'], instance=notfound['instance']) raise exception.NovaException(msg) self._volume_snapshot_check(gcow=delete_info['type']) guest = self._volume_snapshot_check(get_guest=instance) data = {'xml': xml, 'instance': instance, 'volume_id': volume_id} self._volume_snapshot_check(notfound=data)
deleted_lines: if delete_info['type'] != 'qcow2': msg = _('Unknown delete_info type %s') % delete_info['type'] raise exception.NovaException(msg) try: guest = self._host.get_guest(instance) except exception.InstanceNotFound: raise exception.InstanceNotRunning(instance_id=instance.uuid) msg = _('Disk with id: %s ' 'not found attached to instance.') % volume_id LOG.debug('Domain XML: %s', xml, instance=instance) raise exception.NovaException(msg)

subject: Fix race for compute node create record, on compute-start
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-04-12 07:13:40.000000000', 'files': [], 'web_link': 'https://opendev.org/openstack/nova/commit/01c439400c11619dc46308e1b73ce7b8a95d3964', 'message': 'Fix race for compute node create record, on compute-start

A race condition exist where it was possible that two greenthreads
attempt to create a new compute node record in DB for a given compute
node when the compute service is started for the first time. This would
result in a DBDuplicateEntry exception.

In both of these cases, first one wins is an acceptable solution,
so we can swallow the exception safely.

Change-Id: I5502d5c1e5c5c4f90575ab4627bd5e0f6fea565a
Closes-Bug: #1566783

commit_message:
Fix race for compute node create record, on compute-start

A race condition exist where it was possible that two greenthreads
attempt to create a new compute node record in DB for a given compute
node when the compute service is started for the first time. This would
result in a DBDuplicateEntry exception.

In both of these cases, first one wins is an acceptable solution,
so we can swallow the exception safely.

Change-Id: I5502d5c1e5c5c4f90575ab4627bd5e0f6fea565a
Closes-Bug: #1566783

commit_message:
Modify VM's updated_at field on volume actions

Change instance's updated_at property after an attach
and detach volume operation. Also, provide test cases
to validate that the field is updated on attach/detach
volume.

Based on patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/55824

Change-Id: Idb2191b4ad83a2282051ce64846922fbcd0dd597
Closes-Bug: #1250066
Co-Authored-by: ChangBo Guo(gcb) <guochbo@cn.ibm.com>

commit_message:
Set vnic_type correctly for ironic

Ironic ports need to have the vnic_type=baremetal for port to get
correctly bound to the instance. This patch ensures every port that has
its binding updated, heading to an ironic instance, will get the
binding:vnic_type property set to baremetal.

Depends-On: I8fdf55799242642a348597e9b8fffae339402f48
Co-Authored-By: Vasyl Saienko <vsaienko@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: Ia38db1e613f2a5c2788db1da0ac75fe024ee6742
Fixes-bug: #1599836

commit_message:
The server_group_members quota cannot work when bulk boot instances

The server_group_members quota cannot work when bulk boot instances
as the instance_group object was read once from db in:
https://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/nova/tree/nova/compute/api.py#n1137
and was not updated while doing _provision_instances,
when we doing bulk boot instances, the count here will be
incorrect if we don't refresh the instance_group members.
https://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/nova/tree/nova/compute/api.py#n975

This patch move quota check for server group members to
_check_num_instances_quota together with other quota checks.

Change-Id: I0ebe805bd76767d45adaf43a5316365131a0be4c
Closes-bug: #1615883

commit_message:
Filter for ironic uuid

Sometimes you want a node with specific hardware and you happen
to know the uuid from ironic because you just enrolled it.

Implements: blueprint ironic-uuid-scheduler-filter
Change-Id: I1951e1041a2be29496664b8a1d6eea3153707d49

You may obtain # a copy of the License at # # http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0 # # Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software # distributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS, WITHOUT # WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied. See the # License for the specific language governing permissions and limitations # under the License. from oslo_log import log as logging from nova.scheduler import filters LOG = logging.getLogger(__name__) class IronicUuidFilter(filters.BaseHostFilter): """Exact UUID Filter for Ironic.""" def host_passes(self, host_state, spec_obj): """Return True if uuid matches a provided scheduler hint.""" if 'ironic_uuid' not in spec_obj.scheduler_hints: return True # host_state._lock_name is a tuple of the hostname and node-name for # a host. The node-name from the ironic-driver is the ironic node uuid. return (host_state._lock_name[1] == spec_obj.get_scheduler_hint('ironic_uuid'))

commit_message:
Add --image-pull-policy option to zun create command

With the commit 2c6ad5a119b97bc127d7ad3945adfd805c3ce4ba,
we can decide whether to pull the image from docker repos
according to the image pull policy. Add policy support on
client side.

Change-Id: I37c4653670c630fabe79b8ed3927db133ac5d0b5
Depends-On: #If2715d7724fd5336fb25d380f125e1485ca302d0
Closes-bug: 1644072

commit_message:
Set EVENTLET_NO_GREENDNS for IPv6 and dnspython compat

If dnspython is present it causes socket.getaddrinfo() to be
monkeypatched wiht code that does not work with IPv6. To get
around this, the EVENTLET_NO_GREENDNS environment variable
must be set before importing eventlet.

This is resolved in the eventlet upstream code [1], but has not
yet been released. Once our requirements have been raised past
the 0.19.0 release with a version that includes this change we
can remove this workaround.

[1] https://github.com/eventlet/eventlet/commit/52b09becacd23f384cf69ae37d70c893c43e3b13

Change-Id: Id9fe265d67f6e9ea5090bebcacae4a7a9150c5c2
Closes-bug: #1471049
(cherry picked from commit 4f31fb7962a241c13251994c8659595fa2e0693e)
Conflicts:
	cinder/__init__.py

commit_message:
Keystone::Group observe reality implementation

Add override parse_live_resource_data method implementation for
OS::Keystone::Group resource.

Also, add translation rule Resolve for correct handling
domain property.

implements bp get-reality-for-resources

Change-Id: I9bc239c80350fe27c92ca52158639761ba594efc

added_lines: def test_get_live_state(self): group = mock.Mock() group.to_dict.return_value = { 'id': '48ee1f94b77047e592de55a4934c198c', 'domain_id': 'default', 'name': 'fake', 'links': {'self': 'some_link'}, 'description': ''} self.groups.get.return_value = group reality = self.test_group.get_live_state(self.test_group.properties) expected = { 'domain': 'default', 'name': 'fake', 'description': '' } self.assertEqual(set(expected.keys()), set(reality.keys())) for key in expected: self.assertEqual(expected[key], reality[key])

commit_message:
Store security groups in RequestSpec

This adds a security_groups field to the RequestSpec object so
that we can communicate those as part of the request to other
services. Historically this has been a formal RPC parameter to
compute (and later conductor), which was a list of string names.
Putting it here in the request spec means that we can easily
pass a list of real objects, and that we can persist them with
the request spec for later reconstruction of the original request
when appropriate, such as for a rebuild operation.

Change-Id: I2107ec6260954561b5d31b91ad3f27fd325400e2

subject: Add {get_,set_}aggregates to objects.ResourceProvider
revisions:
[{'number': 1, 'created': '2016-08-14 18:45:45.000000000', 'files': [], 'web_link': 'https://opendev.org/openstack/nova/commit/44f7e590bcdc11fa2d40cf6aa3bf996b86ea02a3', 'message': "[WIP] Add {get_,set_}aggregates to objects.ResourceProvider

The Placement API will provider support for associating a list of
aggregate uuids with a resource provider. This is a way of stating
that, for example, a shared storage provider can be used by
compute hosts in aggregates A, B and C.

This change implements the basic get and set functionality required
on the ResourceProvider object as callable methods. Using fields was
also considered but given the precedent with set_inventory and
friends, methods were chosen. Because methods were chosen, explict
get and set-based names were used to avoid confusion with fields or
properties.

This remains a WIP for at least two reasons:

* When using the placement database we must create a new
  PlacementAggregate in the database for any previously unseen
  aggregate uuid. When using the api database, it is not clear that
  this is the desired behavior. Should we error out then? If we do
  not error, we'll be creating aggregates without names. Is that
  okay. There are TODOs in set_aggregates marking the area of
  concern.

* Thinking about the above issue led to many different rounds of
  attempts to come up with a coherent way of implementing
  set_aggregates. That iteration involved many different strategies
  and the results are a hodgepodge.

  The current way seems to work but feel untidy and inefficient.
  It could definitely be done with fewer queries, but it is not
  clear if doing so would be easier to read. Improvement left as
  an exericse for reviewers.

There will be a followup to this patch which implements the HTTP
handling of aggregates in the placement API.

As the guts of the complexity are in the database handling, tests
are on the functional side.

Change-Id: I95258e632f2c034e5b7b803a753f393ad715ca50
Partially-Implements: blueprint generic-resource-pools

"}, {'number': 6, 'created': '2016-08-30 15:30:59.000000000', 'files': [], 'web_link': 'https://opendev.org/openstack/nova/commit/95985e40227e2529dfaa2a7fec22db5d1b245d9e', 'message': "Add {get_,set_}aggregates to objects.ResourceProvider

The Placement API will provider support for associating a list of
aggregate uuids with a resource provider. This is a way of stating
that, for example, a shared storage provider can be used by
compute hosts in aggregates A, B and C.

This change implements the basic get and set functionality required
on the ResourceProvider object as callable methods. Using fields was
also considered but given the precedent with set_inventory and
friends, methods were chosen. Because methods were chosen, explict
get and set-based names were used to avoid confusion with fields or
properties.

This is _not done_ but needs wider review because:

* When using the placement database we must create a new
  PlacementAggregate in the database for any previously unseen
  aggregate uuid. When using the api database, it is not clear that
  this is the desired behavior. Should we error out then? If we do
  not error, we'll be creating aggregates without names. Is that
  okay. There are TODOs in set_aggregates marking the area of
  concern.

* Thinking about the above issue led to many different rounds of
  attempts to come up with a coherent way of implementing
  set_aggregates. That iteration involved many different strategies
  and the results are a hodgepodge.

  The current way seems to work but feel untidy and inefficient.
  It could definitely be done with fewer queries, but it is not
  clear if doing so would be easier to read. Improvement left as
  an exericse for reviewers.

There will be a followup to this patch which implements the HTTP
handling of aggregates in the placement API.

As the guts of the complexity are in the database handling, tests
are on the functional side.

Change-Id: I95258e632f2c034e5b7b803a753f393ad715ca50
Partially-Implements: blueprint generic-resource-pools

commit_message:
Add {get_,set_}aggregates to objects.ResourceProvider

The Placement API will provide support for associating a list of
aggregate uuids with a resource provider. This is a way of stating
that, for example, a shared storage provider can be used by
compute hosts in aggregates A, B and C.

This change implements the basic get and set functionality required
on the ResourceProvider object as callable methods. Using fields was
also considered but given the precedent with set_inventory and
friends, methods were chosen. Because methods were chosen, explict
get and set-based names were used to avoid confusion with fields or
properties. Since the methods will only be called from the placement
API service, they are not remotable.

The aggregates are stored in the PlacementAggregates model, which is
a recently introduced new table (in Change
Id0355cb022f68e962af306ff04cf724d22b68d19).

As the guts of the complexity are in the database handling, tests
are on the functional side.

Change-Id: I95258e632f2c034e5b7b803a753f393ad715ca50
Partially-Implements: blueprint generic-resource-pools-ocata

added_lines: class TestResourceProviderAggregates(test.NoDBTestCase): USES_DB_SELF = True def setUp(self): super(TestResourceProviderAggregates, self).setUp() self.useFixture(fixtures.Database(database='placement')) # We need both the main and api databases for # non-placement-db aggregates to work. self.useFixture(fixtures.Database(database='main')) self.useFixture(fixtures.Database(database='api')) self.context = context.RequestContext('fake-user', 'fake-project') def test_set_and_get_new_aggregates(self): rp = objects.ResourceProvider( context=self.context, uuid=uuidsentinel.rp_uuid, name=uuidsentinel.rp_name ) rp.create() aggregate_uuids = [uuidsentinel.agg_a, uuidsentinel.agg_b] rp.set_aggregates(aggregate_uuids) read_aggregate_uuids = rp.get_aggregates() self.assertItemsEqual(aggregate_uuids, read_aggregate_uuids) # Since get_aggregates always does a new query this is # mostly nonsense but is here for completeness. read_rp = objects.ResourceProvider.get_by_uuid( self.context, uuidsentinel.rp_uuid) re_read_aggregate_uuids = read_rp.get_aggregates() self.assertItemsEqual(aggregate_uuids, re_read_aggregate_uuids) # TODO(cdent): For the moment this test doesn't actually test # anything new because the aggregate is created in the api # database and set_aggregates currently only talks the placement # database. In the real world this could be the same database, # but under testing situations it is a different in ram databases. def test_set_and_get_existing_aggregates(self): agg_uuid = uuidsentinel.agg_uuid aggregate = objects.Aggregate( context=self.context, uuid=agg_uuid, name='an aggregate' ) aggregate.create() rp = objects.ResourceProvider( context=self.context, uuid=uuidsentinel.rp_uuid, name=uuidsentinel.rp_name ) rp.create() rp.set_aggregates([agg_uuid]) read_aggregate_uuids = rp.get_aggregates() self.assertItemsEqual([agg_uuid], read_aggregate_uuids) def test_set_aggregates_is_replace(self): rp = objects.ResourceProvider( context=self.context, uuid=uuidsentinel.rp_uuid, name=uuidsentinel.rp_name ) rp.create() start_aggregate_uuids = [uuidsentinel.agg_a, uuidsentinel.agg_b] rp.set_aggregates(start_aggregate_uuids) read_aggregate_uuids = rp.get_aggregates() self.assertItemsEqual(start_aggregate_uuids, read_aggregate_uuids) rp.set_aggregates([uuidsentinel.agg_a]) read_aggregate_uuids = rp.get_aggregates() self.assertNotIn(uuidsentinel.agg_b, read_aggregate_uuids) self.assertIn(uuidsentinel.agg_a, read_aggregate_uuids)

commit_message:
Remove KEYSTONE_CATALOG_BACKEND from magnum plugin

Devstack has removed KEYSTONE_CATALOG_BACKEND from it's
repo: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/391380

Due to above change gate tests are failing, we should
remove it from magnum plugin as well. Refer below for
it's deprecation and removal:-
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-dev/2016-February/086272.html

Change-Id: I9ad6e0577918e811e9dd051b56aa69bfe2c391a0
Closes-Bug: #1644085

commit_message:
Returns 1.5.0 for python-heatclient

Release 1.6.0 has broken all rally gate jobs and
is subsequently blocking Rally and other projects
with voting rally jobs (e.g. Neutron) from merging
changes.

commit_message:
Fix py27 CI failure

the py27 CI failed due to tox 2.5.0 release. The command
in tox.ini is required now[1].

This patch refactored the code tree to make CI work.

[1]:
https://github.com/tox-dev/tox/blob/1e888ce9b87d87045479ed4c320be803b05b0f38/CHANGELOG#L40

deleted_lines: @mock.patch.object(pb.Profile, 'delete') @mock.patch.object(service.EngineService, 'profile_find') def test_profile_delete(self, mock_find, mock_delete): x_obj = mock.Mock(id='PROFILE_ID') mock_find.return_value = x_obj mock_delete.return_value = None result = self.eng.profile_delete(self.ctx, 'FAKE_PROFILE') self.assertIsNone(result) mock_find.assert_called_once_with(self.ctx, 'FAKE_PROFILE') mock_delete.assert_called_once_with(self.ctx, 'PROFILE_ID') @mock.patch.object(service.EngineService, 'profile_find') def test_profile_delete_not_found(self, mock_find): mock_find.side_effect = exc.ResourceNotFound(type='profile', id='Bogus') ex = self.assertRaises(rpc.ExpectedException, self.eng.profile_delete, self.ctx, 'Bogus') self.assertEqual(exc.ResourceNotFound, ex.exc_info[0]) self.assertEqual('The profile (Bogus) could not be found.', six.text_type(ex.exc_info[1])) mock_find.assert_called_once_with(self.ctx, 'Bogus') @mock.patch.object(pb.Profile, 'delete') @mock.patch.object(service.EngineService, 'profile_find') def test_profile_delete_profile_in_use(self, mock_find, mock_delete): x_obj = mock.Mock(id='PROFILE_ID') mock_find.return_value = x_obj err = exc.EResourceBusy(type='profile', id='PROFILE_ID') mock_delete.side_effect = err ex = self.assertRaises(rpc.ExpectedException, self.eng.profile_delete, self.ctx, 'FAKE_PROFILE') self.assertEqual(exc.ResourceInUse, ex.exc_info[0]) self.assertEqual("The profile FAKE_PROFILE cannot be deleted: still " "referenced by some clusters and/or nodes.", six.text_type(ex.exc_info[1])) mock_find.assert_called_once_with(self.ctx, 'FAKE_PROFILE') mock_delete.assert_called_once_with(self.ctx, 'PROFILE_ID')

commit_message:
Fix backup NFS share mount with default backup_mount_options

Now, if backup_mount_options in not set, NFS Backup driver
passes empty dict to RemoteFsClient. It cause an error when
RemoteFsClient mounts the share because it passes '-o {}' params.

According to [1] we should pass None to RemoteFsClient if no
backup_mount_options was specified.

[1] https://github.com/openstack/os-brick/blob/master/os_brick/remotefs/remotefs.py#L129-L130

Change-Id: Ief874332a71ff77c88a65e2d631457b831472236
Closes-Bug: #1529566
(cherry picked from commit ca25d7af9768182723a64fd26be3a8a41142c001)

commit_message:
Add host check while create snapshot

We may create a volume but the volume was not been scheduled for some
reasons(e.g. The disk space is unavailable, cinder-volume service is
down, etc...). Although this volume is in error status, we can force
create snapshot using `--force` flag, that's make no sense. What's worse,
it may carry some unexpected error: We can delete this error volume before
cleanup the snapshot, but we can't delete the snapshot any more via API for
its prarent volume not found. This patch just raises an InvalidVolume
exception when we create a snapshot on a volume without host. In
addtion, the volume state is mutable so I think it is not 100% reliable,
the user may reset state w/o checking host state. I think we need check
host state before go forward to create snapshot on it.

Change-Id: Ifb9388cc76c1ff8d2e7f5b24710acbe95b602825
Closes-Bug: #1641294

commit_message:
Don't pass deprecated validation param to overcloud deploy

--validation-errors-fatal was turned on by default in Newton and
will be removed in Ocata.  We shouldn't be passing the deprecated
parameter to either of those releases now.  It is left for the
older stable releases to ensure patches don't break validations.

Change-Id: Id8183bf86e5ea1e384f590e02e0daef0f053713d
git_command: git fetch https://review.opendev.org/openstack/tripleo-ci refs/changes/72/397972/1 && git format-patch -1 --stdout FETCH_HEAD
added_lines: # --validation-errors-fatal was deprecated in newton and removed in ocata if [[ "${STABLE_RELEASE}" =~ ^(liberty|mitaka)$ ]]; then OVERCLOUD_VALIDATE_ARGS=${OVERCLOUD_VALIDATE_ARGS-"--validation-errors-fatal --validation-warnings-fatal"} else OVERCLOUD_VALIDATE_ARGS=${OVERCLOUD_VALIDATE_ARGS-"--validation-warnings-fatal"} fi

commit_message:
Object upload in swift occasionally fails with 'TypeError'.

Data upload to swift store occasionally fails due to invalid
keystone token. In which case, the retry operation uses the same
StringIO object for the source. As it was read in the
first attempt, it will end up with a data of length 0 byte causing
this issue. Moving it inside the retry block, so it constructs a
new one on each retry.

Change-Id: Ic335815a25fb18b8b547add4e5decd531ca1d93d
Closes-Bug: #1642489

Below if check # is just a hack to handle the same till it's fixed in # the community if isinstance(result['error'], TypeError): # Upload to swift store failed due to missing # 'content-length' param in response headers from # swiftclient. missing_content_length['value'] = True return True if missing_content_length: # Handle 'TypeError' failure and log a message, instead of # raising exception LOG.warning(_LI('Unable to update swift store for instance:' ' %s, due to missing content-length in' ' response. commit_message:
Object upload in swift occasionally fails with 'TypeError'.

Data upload to swift store occasionally fails due to invalid
keystone token. In which case, the retry operation uses the same
StringIO object for the source. As it was read in the
first attempt, it will end up with a data of length 0 byte causing
this issue. Moving it inside the retry block, so it constructs a
new one on each retry.

Change-Id: Ic335815a25fb18b8b547add4e5decd531ca1d93d
Closes-Bug: #1642489

commit_message:
Add __ne__ built-in function

In Python 3 __ne__ by default delegates to __eq__ and inverts the
result, but in Python 2 they urge you to define __ne__ when you
define __eq__ for it to work properly [1].There are no implied
relationships among the comparison operators. The truth of x==y
does not imply that x!=y is false. Accordingly, when defining __eq__(),
one should also define __ne__() so that the operators will behave as
expected.
[1]https://docs.python.org/2/reference/datamodel.html#object.__ne_

Change-Id: Id87d06ebd3b6e437152a91981f011cdc63a08b7f
git_command: git fetch https://review.opendev.org/openstack/python-manilaclient refs/changes/37/401137/1 && git format-patch -1 --stdout FETCH_HEAD
added_lines: def __ne__(self, other): return not self.__eq__(other) def __ne__(self, other): return not self.__eq__(other)

commit_message:
Fix reconstruct to return an error when memory allocation failed

As like current code, if we do go jump to just "out" section when
memory allocation failed, liberaurecode/PyECLib will report it as
success. However, in fact, the returned binary is not the one
reconstructed. This patch fixes liberasurecode_reconstruct to return
error code (ENOMEM) if either malloc or memset for working space is
failed.

Change-Id: I7bfc481c7a9bbc64288760df2dc6053c57657b41

commit_message:
Do not ignore pm_port for Drac drivers

Allow using a non-standard port for the Drac drivers.

This patch is also adding unittests for pxe_drac and pxe_ipmitool
drivers.

Change-Id: Id4bf87ef5022d67b8720404c86ebbe28161405d3
Closes-Bug: #1643574

Delete the create_resources functions that do not take effect

1) The create_resources functions have no effect, so we can remove them.
2) Update releated options and tests.

commit_message:
Adds distribution ID option to diskimage-create.sh

This patch adds a distribution ID option to the diskimage-create.sh
script used to create amphora images.  This will allow octavia
to control the timing of the transition to a new default release.
For Mitaka it will default to "trusty".

Change-Id: I5fba1edae923673def33706c9ecd9e51fcffe243
Closes-Bug: 1642756
(cherry picked from commit 2db260c95a326404d4ea4a33efe6c4151f29fb59)
git_command: git fetch https://review.opendev.org/openstack/octavia refs/changes/76/399276/2 && git format-patch -1 --stdout FETCH_HEAD
added_lines: echo " [-d **trusty** | xenial | <other release id> ]" echo " '-d' distribution release id (default: trusty)"while getopts "a:b:c:d:hi:o:t:r:s:vw:" opt; do d) AMP_DIB_RELEASE=$OPTARG ;;export DIB_RELEASE=${AMP_DIB_RELEASE:-"trusty"}

commit_message:
Pin HTTP response codes to API microversions

Some methods could have different response codes depending
on version, like EvacuateController._evacuate should return
202 code instead of 200 because it is asynchronous, this new
decorator enables to change response codes in new versions
preserving backward compatibility.

Change-Id: I2c081878c18f2905a9509cfdbc84deec32127154

commit_message:
Enable bridge firewalling if iptables are used

With the plan [1] to stop enabling it by Neutron iptables firewall
driver itself, deployment tools should catch up and enable the firewall
themselves.

This is needed for distributions that decided to disable the kernel
firewall by default (upstream kernel has it enabled). This is also
needed for distributions that ship newer kernels but don't load the
br_netfilter module before starting nova-network or Neutron iptables
firewall driver. In the latter case, firewall may not work, depending on
the order of operations executed by the driver.

To isolate devstack setups from the difference in distribution
kernel configuration and version, the following steps are done:

- we load bridge kernel module, and br_netfilter if present, to get
  access to sysctl knobs controlling the firewall;
- once knobs are available, we unconditionally set them to 1, to make
  sure the firewall is in effect.

More details at:
http://wiki.libvirt.org/page/Net.bridge.bridge-nf-call_and_sysctl.conf

[1] I9137ea017624ac92a05f73863b77f9ee4681bbe7

Change-Id: Id6bfd9595f0772a63d1096ef83ebbb6cd630fafd
Related-Bug: #1622914
(cherry picked from commit b3a210f643989603d192b32a40b2001664f8ed73)

commit_message:
Add support for Oslo Policies to Trove

The Oslo Policy library provides support for RBAC policy enforcement
across all OpenStack services.

Change-Id: Ifee24ab34a897152e3a0d001628558f95269e80f
Implements: blueprint trove-policy

Proposed Change =============== Add Oslo policy check calls on all user-facing APIs. [1]_ Also see `Appendix`_ for the list of proposed rules. The checks will be implemented by means of Oslo policy 'enforce' call at the beginning of each Trove API. commit_message:
DiskFilter: Ignore root when booting from volume

When booting from volume, scheduler should not use the flavor's root
disk to decide if the instance can be booted. Flavor's root disk only
taken into account when using an image for the boot.

Closes-Bug: #1334974

Change-Id: I3340985f632a5406c47c0d691e6286c9a5372ae0

commit_message:
refresh instances_path when shared storage used

When doing Live migration with shared storage, it happens erratically,
that the check for the shared storage test_file fails. Because the shared
volume is under heavy IO (many instances on many compute nodes) the client
does not immediately sees the new content of the folder. This delay
could take up to 30s.
This can be fixed if the client is forced to refresh the directories
content, which can be achieved by 'touch' on the directory. Doing so,
the test_file is visibile instantly, within ms.
The patch adds a 'touch' on instances_path in check_shared_storage_test_file,
before checking the existence of the file.

Change-Id: I16be39142278517f43e6eca3441a56cbc9561113
Closes-Bug: #1617299
(cherry picked from commit 1af73d1fb3169c5b3cce77d94316922496bbaf9a)

commit_message:
Validation of router_ids insertion with column selection

Currently, FWaaS Column Selection/Filtering does not work correctly
without 'id'.  This commit adds the validation of the params for
column selection.

  GET v2.0/fw/firewalls with fields 'router_ids'
    -> Add 'id' into fields and remove it after router_ids insertion.

  GET v2.0/fw/firewalls with fields without 'router_ids'
    -> Skip router_ids insertion.

Change-Id: I5bcd148de524af802f01e4e5444a6e605318954f
Closes-Bug: #1520601

commit_message:
Add admin_password parameter setting

Now ,we actually use admin_token to set keystone password for the
admin user, but admin_token will be removed in a later release,
so add admin_password parameter setting.

Change-Id: I33999503d42fd0405fddc5dce906f1518ac1e732
Closes-Bug: #1644158

commit_message:
Fix ovs 2.4 to 2.5 upgrade - minor update non controllers

In I9b1f0eaa0d36a28e20b507bec6a4e9b3af1781ae and
I11fcf688982ceda5eef7afc8904afae44300c2d9 we landed a workaround
for the openvswitch 2.4 to 2.5 upgrade discussed in the bug below.

Unfortunately testing has revealed a problem with the minor update
case specifically for non controllers. It seems we would exit
before the ovs workaround has had a chance to execute. This moves
the block up a few lines to avoid this condition. As with the
other two reviews noted here, this will need to go into newton
and then mitaka too.

Change-Id: If905de82d96302334ebe02de9c43f00faed9b72b
Related-Bug: 1635205
(cherry picked from commit 5a472f196e3392bf4187d4498f7c50db596f360a)

commit_message:
Fix Galera_common.grow/shrink to propogate exceptions

The grow and shrink operations in Galera_common were eating exceptions.
This change passes the exceptions back and adds unit tests to
ensure such.

Change-Id: I3202d6d4daa77a8a185a427b31b2187eab4d82e9
Closes-bug: 1634627

commit_message:
Raise tooz error when unexpected last entries found

When the file driver is deleting a group, the only
thing left in that group directory should be the
group metadata file, so before deleting the group
add a check that makes sure the leftover file is
actually the metadata file (and not something else).

Change-Id: I63a1e2cf95d524fea5e1c009ecc951670e2e8f5c
git_command: git fetch https://review.opendev.org/openstack/tooz refs/changes/64/347664/1 && git format-patch -1 --stdout FETCH_HEAD
added_lines: import os import fixtures def test_leftover_file(self): fixture = self.useFixture(fixtures.TempDir()) file_path = fixture.path url = 'file://%s' % file_path coord = coordination.get_coordinator(url, self._FAKE_MEMBER_ID) coord.start() self.addCleanup(coord.stop) coord.create_group(b"my_group").get() safe_group_id = coord._make_filesystem_safe(b"my_group") with open(os.path.join(file_path, 'groups', safe_group_id, "junk.txt"), "wb"): pass os.unlink(os.path.join(file_path, 'groups', safe_group_id, '.metadata')) self.assertRaises(coordination.ToozError, coord.delete_group(b"my_group").get)

commit_message:
RBD: prevent creation of encrypted volumes

At the moment RBD volume encryption is not supported.  Libvirt needs
support for non-block encryption and nova will need a few changes as
well.  Efforts are underway to resolve this, but in the mean time it's
very confusing to users when we allow them to create encrypted volumes
using volume types as stated in the documentation.  Encryption of the
volume will eventually fail, but allowing this creation creates an
unreasonable expectation.

This patch prevents encrypted volume creation for RBD until support has
landed.  At that time, this patch should be reverted.

Change-Id: I0f071a4aea2d6454b71d83055e87d87b9efcc014

commit_message:
Remove 95pct and median from default archive policies

This should makes the default at least 25% faster for metricd, which is
quite of a big deal. These are still available as custom methods to add
anyway.

commit_message:
Avoid creating tasks with empty nodes list

For a granular deploy when a node is deleted and deployment is
triggered the list of nodes for deploy is empty and all remaining nodes
are in the list of affected nodes. This causes nonreexecutable tasks to
appear in the list of tasks with empty uids array.
This patch fixes the problem.

Change-Id: I7377c50df87d1f2448ac2bc775840738d535d7fd
Closes-Bug: #1628500
(cherry picked from commit 70ebe005390bfa475801dcba8b3dc1374996a994)

commit_message:
Remove more usages of Tempest core code

Moving forward with efforts to use less tempest core in favor of
stable tempest.lib, this patch removes usages of some decorators from
tempest.test (based on [1]) - The decorator just calls testtools.testcase.attr
and so we can use it directly as suggested in [2].
It also directly uses idempotent_id decorator which is already in
tempest.lib and is what's used in tempest.test anyway.

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/374719/
[2] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/373972/

Change-Id: If4ceeaeb217ad46ecc5f4bb55bb393cef870072f

commit_message:
Add necessary parameters for encrypted volumes support

If barbican is set, it will configure cinder and nova-compute with
the necessary parameters to enable encrypted volumes to be created if
requested.

Change-Id: Id13811cf8e090706c590ffff46c237ff8131efd9

commit_message:
Fix cluster progress calculation if Astute didn't send it

Deploying status has been removed, we assume that the node is
int deploying status if status is provisioned or ready, and
progress is greater than zero.

Change-Id: Ia64b5c9e54591892685f1e1806124f2523bcb40b
(cherry picked from commit 3ed600aa3e6b67130da4d1dd8952a9d36bc1a849)

commit_message:
Introduce tags_metadata file for plugins

'tags_metadata.yaml' file contains set of tags for tasks
serialization. These tags can be used in roles introduced
by the plugin.

(cherry picked from commit e8ed5cba839beb9c93b6259332848db75e9d4efc)
Implements: blueprint role-decomposition
Change-Id: I1e68a240b2fe535188404eb47c23b875a4616f2a

commit_message:
Revert "Update devstack keystone_authtoken config to fit with keystone v3"

This reverts commit df8bf9c8f85fb1c1aa27c803a78868f54a42e1ea.
That patch renamed keys of the configuration properties of the
keystone_authtoken settings group, thus breaking config file
compatibility.

Change-Id: I8fd3b3211e75207cf6061eef6f038ea045d9dbfe
